Nutrition of obese children: No breakfast and snacks for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 weigh more than the norm; while 9% of schoolchildren are overweight, 5% suffer from obesity.
According to a recent study, children who suffer from obesity usually come from families who lead an unhealthy lifestyle.
We see again the importance of the environment and the patterns of behavior accompanying a person for his or her healthy development.
For example, sausages appear on the tables of obese children, almost twice as often as in families with children with normal weight.
More than 19% of obese children ate free potatoes for dinner on the eve of a survey related to an educational event called Obesity is not a coincidence.
Moreover, the families of children who suffer from obesity do not engage in sports. However, this applies to most of the families of modern schoolchildren - only 15% of children said that their parents find time to practice sports at least once a week.
The study was conducted on 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last academic year; it was attended by nearly 900 elementary school students throughout Bohemia.
Obesity is not a coincidence for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company Vseobecná sarodní ink<0xC5><0xAF><0xC5><0xA1>tovna and the company Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 schoolchildren of 4-8 grades have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate exercise exercise are the main determining factors that cause the rapidly growing number of children who are either suffering from overweight or obesity.
“For example, only half of the respondents said they ate five meals a day, according to the breakfast-breakfast-breakfast-breakfast-breakfast-breakfast-dinner scheme, and that’s one of the essential conditions for proper nutrition,” the study concluded.
No lunches and snacks in the evening
Experts warn that for healthy development, even relative details such as the regular time of family breakfast are important.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of schoolchildren eat breakfast together.
In most families, breakfast is served separately.
The worst finding is that one in every 10 families don’t have breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the correct daily diet.
The study found that roasted food is more commonly consumed in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet cooling drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40% of children regularly practice sports, this figure is more than doubled – up to 15% – when it comes to their parents.
Set up your own menu.
In another part of the study, the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to prepare their own menu based on the suggested products and based on their tastes and preferences.
"Preferences in eating for Czech children aged 12-15 years are far from the ideal when it comes to healthy eating."
Their favorite food includes a large number of bitter, meaty and sweet dishes.
“Special concern is the great popularity of sweet cooling beverages,” the study concludes.
As the main lunch dish, pasta beat the bird with a small overweight.
However, the children had virtually no interest in beans, fish and vegetable dishes.
A desire for a healthy lifestyle
The study also found that children are willing to change their eating habits provided they are provided with relevant information.
“Many of the study’s control group participants demonstrated a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they filled out a questionnaire after completing the lecture Obesity is not a coincidence,” the project’s findings said.
This was especially noticeable, for example, in the case of sweet cooling drinks - more children began to prefer just water.
In addition, as the main dish, children were more often noted for birds and fish, limiting the amount of sweet dishes and baking.
