V Need for Speed: Escape takes place in America.
<0xE2><0x80><0xA2> Review
What was supposed to be a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and negligent mistakes.
The ambitions were satisfied to a certain extent, but it doesn’t matter, as no one clearly wanted to do the extra work.
Before the release of the new version with the subheading "Escape" was associated with great hopes.
It was expected to shift the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; demo versions indicated that the game would occupy a decent place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main character comes out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end, a lot is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the overall impression is lost by a few unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for several years.
And so, in fact, it is not a mistake, but a manifestation of an inexplicable lenin of developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You become part of the story, whose main character, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race across America.
You’ll be in a car on the west coast in San Francisco, and your task is to get to New York first.
This idea has several interesting features.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes place on its own route, individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
Therefore, there is no feeling that the same thing happens all the time in the game.
Despite the fact that the graph is at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is nice to watch on some tracks.
However, the game does not create strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs or high in the snowy mountains is very pleasant.
In addition, the race from time to time revives an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert you get into a sandstorm, which significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you need to be careful not to fall under the avalanche.
The individual races are fairly well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that is enough.
For a while you’re trying to bypass several opponents (essentially a regular race); then you’re trying to improve the time (a standard second-time race); or you’re competing with one opponent.
Among other things, from time to time you encounter the police, which further complicates your task.
The components outside the car are new.
It’s just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
There's nothing complicated.
Although it’s surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (only three to be precise).
Actually, it turns out to be good for the game because it does not bode well; considering all of the above, it is one of the things that make the game more entertaining.
The race model follows the footsteps of previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a drawback.
If you are looking for imitation of real life, you will have to look elsewhere.
And yet this driving model is very suitable for dynamic races, although you can find better options on the market.
So far it's all very well.
After a while, however, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don’t expect complex transformations and collisions from such a game, but if you have no idea before a collision with an object, how your machine will behave, something is wrong.
Typically, by rolling or passing machines in a dense stream, you sometimes touch another machine slightly. And yet sometimes in almost similar situations, your machine starts to swing furiously.
Or it's broken down.
This is not so important thanks to the restart system, but this is enough to spoil the fun.
The restarts are arranged so that if you break up or leave the track far away, the game will return you to the point where it was interrupted.
However, only five reboots are available for each race.
If you use them all, you will have to start the race from the very beginning.
This is useful in case something doesn’t work, but you can’t fully rely on it.
Sometimes restarts are not enough, and you have to learn a separate section of the race.
An important disadvantage of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to pass in a certain way, otherwise you just won’t log in.
In other cases, you encounter civilian cars in a certain place in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier, or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see your opponent move easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, while when you’re there, the cars are already positioned in such a way that you either need to go around them or lower the speed.
It doesn’t matter when you’re next to them; everything is arranged in such a way that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors have other advantages.
During the game, you discover several places where, regardless of the time, the same opponent will wreak havoc on you in the same place.
This is especially evident at the end of the game, on the long bridge where you go in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent has to stand in front of you no matter what.
The fact is, when he drives in front of you, he deteriorates you overview, which leads to one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand the attempt to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it is so obvious that it quickly starts to cause irritation.
Unfortunately, despite the simple driving model, the game is fun and sometimes so full of events that you don’t have time to pay attention to what’s happening around you.
It doesn’t matter what makes you miss – a concept with fifty unique tracks, a sequence of races or something else.
The idea of changing cars during races is unusual.
You need to track the gasoline along the way, as it is on them that your car can change, despite the fact that in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Machines are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars are for straight sections of the road; and exotic super-sports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain tracks.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; it’s the individual track races that you’ll learn as the game progresses.
Here you win for your personal cause both medals and points, common to the challenges and story modes.
Many options are available to get a higher level of driving: from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is associated with the online Autolog feature, which, among other things, compares the results you achieve with the results of other players, and provides communication with the public.
Here’s another drawback that’s hard to understand; this is an example of the last race in a sequence.
You and your car get into the subway tunnel (let’s assume that’s the case), where you’re strolling along the rails in the dark (let’s assume that’s the case).
Your speedometer shows figures from 150 to 200 km/h (let’s say that) when suddenly a subway train crashes at your back, turning your car into a metallic chest.
For a few days, our editorial board discussed whether nobody really thought for a second at the time of creating the game, or whether its creators really thought of us as such.
The technical component of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from the video is largely pleasant, sometimes even stunning.
Although it is a pity that at some critical moments the quality of the recording, sometimes quite strongly, is declining.
This is especially true for events with a large number of participants, where a good record would not help you either.
Sound in order; soundtrack - to the lover.
To please as wide a youth audience as possible, the soundtrack ‘compositions of different styles’ has come in; but it’s unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
Need for Speed: Running is a bit of a mess.
If the game avoided clearly unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that Running is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
In any case, the game leaves a feeling of incompleteness.
Of course, it’s a good entertainment, but be prepared for the shortcomings to blind you as an airport headlight.
