History of the brand:
IBM is entering the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find a word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest is likely to be “long-lasting”.
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was set by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson the Elder.
He believed in his motto that many world problems can be easily solved if people want to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant was developed (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
What’s more, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a constant move towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, although it was not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, this has enabled us to transform technology, business and company.
In the next 100 years, we hope to achieve even more,” said Samuel J. Palmizano, the company’s current CEO on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complex system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of care for employees as well as Batya in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, an elegant outfit, and a complex bonus system.
