The dynamics of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Because travel to the West was severely restricted, the travel agencies of the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, during the holidays, Czech tourists travelled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia. Then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which resulted in significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual trips to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was required; otherwise, individual travel was not possible.
At the time, the travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but it was either to stay in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that's not all.
Currency permits were required for travel to the West. It was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was impossible to obtain money (western currency) for a trip to the West without a currency permit.
Most often, the Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit remains to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus undergone a real revolution.
While until 1989 the holidays in the DPR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989 we could not freely visit the most popular Croatia today, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In early 1990, the need to obtain a visa to the neighbouring countries of Western Europe was abolished, which led to a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not be satisfied with travelling to the West. Everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was lacking in a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of Czech tourism in that period was the desire to bring their own food (canned, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown. After decades our tourists can finally freely buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income increased, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, the increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, airline tickets have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to book wholesale discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed countries of the world except the United States. This made our travels even easier.
The next major event in the history of post-revolution travel took place in 2000. Great demand led to the first historically direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights are delivering Czech tourists to warm exotic countries. This winter flights from the Czech Republic will be sent to twelve exotic destinations.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, occurred in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. canceled the visa requirement for Czech tourists. Our country, thus, has forever joined the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during the holiday abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
