After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
It's easy - you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized it’s not hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of the recently published report on European cyber populism at the British Research Centre DEMOS.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so big, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to highlight the necessary demographics with scientific accuracy – which marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then placed an advertisement for them, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the advertisement offered the user to go through a survey with questions about the level of their education, their attitude to violence and their own rejection.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 participants of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – not even leaving the office.
“This is a completely new way to conduct research,” says Bartlett.
Some results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who just hide behind the monitor.”
The DEMOS work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and politicians use the site to study everything in the world – from health issues to social trends that are expressed in ‘lights’, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-recent information” is sparking a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles titled the site by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it gives you the opportunity to study people who can’t approach on the street with a notebook.
“Earlier, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to join the party and they would never have accepted you,” Bartlett said.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you’re addressing them directly.”
Others say that with the help of this site it would be possible to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Meghan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and colleagues found that students who discussed their drunk feats on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as their dormitory mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drunk statuses.
“You can’t solve the problem without identifying it,” said Washington Post’s Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
“We found a way to identify children from the risk group who otherwise would not have been detected.”
Facebook also continuously retrieves various types of data about its users.
The data processing team of the site processed statistics of the relationship status and Valentine's Day, the election of voters in mid-term in 2010, as well as the National Index of Happiness (mainly using information, to which the website should be accessed only by them, - the champions of cyber-freedom.
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend located thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a research they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strictly defined standards for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users have at least thought about what a researcher can look at their profiles,” says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using public-access student pages on Facebook.
“As far as they could have imagined, it was only between them and their friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that the research object is extremely honest.
It is not possible on Facebook to know how much information in the profile and on the user’s page is true.
“What you’re saying on Facebook and what you’re doing outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selvin says.
