Court to Approve ‘Transition to Digital Television’ in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has made in recent years.
The Supreme Court rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which moves the so-called "transition to digital television" from 2021 to 2015, as there were no eight votes required for its cancellation.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers by issuing a decree detailing the actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected because of the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to declare the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of the radio and television program is a law enshrined in the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and re-legislation.
Only Salvador, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to reject the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said he disagreed with the project's arguments in the sense that the federal executive could not determine by common rules the measures for which the state administration should prepare.
“I also don’t think that if this happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” and recalled that planning state policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, has to do with the federal executive authority, which has a constitutional government mandate.
Replacement of analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years, leading to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of digital transformation, which includes meeting public needs, which has not only a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These questions, he said, “require the work of the entire system formed on the principle of state economic governance, including the group of authorities that the Constitution unites into state executive power.”
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and did so with the help of the executive, despite the presence of narrow technical institutions.
From this, it cannot be concluded that the Government, by adopting the Decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of Congress, ensures that the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly are complied with in the administrative sphere.
