In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay’s protest and a withdrawal for consultations of its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has presided over the G20, a group formed from the most developed and developing countries since November, and has, in essence, with the South American country since January of this year, an agreement to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has sought to accelerate the conclusion of tax-exchange agreements to leave the “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, made up of countries that do not benefit from international tax cooperation standards.
As regards the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
