MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social Protection leads a study on finding a gene for obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the gene of obesity in children and young people, which has been named the “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescent Age” protocol, which will provide an account of the signs associated with obesity.
In his statement, the head of the Medical Research Division of the Specialized Biochemistry Hospital of the 21st Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had been assembled.
This team is assisted by specialists and graduates of the National Institute of Health (NIPH) and the Centre for Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children will be conducted every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Quautemoc (western Mexico), and from October 8 the events are held at the sports center in Nesaualcoyotl (east Mexico).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children is reached, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (South Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (North Mexico).
He explained that the aim of this study was to understand the components and importance of genetics regarding the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated, and the main goal is to gather 3,000 children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 with the permission of parents and under their supervision to complete individual nutrition surveys.
They will also be asked about physical activity and a history of family hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to the onset of diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that anthropometric measurements of all participants will be carried out on Saturday (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure measurement and glucose levels, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to identify the genes associated with childbirth).
Cross López said the study reflects health care professionals’ concerns about worrying weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 show that in just 6 years, there was growth: in boys 77 percent were obese, in girls 47 percent; in terms of excess weight, there was also a significant growth,” said MSSI specialist.
He said the rationale for the search for markers was based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican is a descendant of 65 percent of American Native Americans, 30 percent of Europeans and five percent of Africans, and that the condition affected the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that essentially, the result of obesity’s genetics is the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for participants is a comprehensive assessment of children, which can determine whether they have any degree of excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of a metabolic disorder and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with complete confidentiality, the doctors pass it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the dimensions and lifestyle changes that must be undertaken to avoid the disease.
Cross López explained that there are three main reasons that provoke obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or a lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day in front of the TV, and the use of transportation in the clouds.
This is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. an increase in the consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tomatoes, bread, pizzas, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM will be able to avoid cracks
Rafael Errera, a researcher at UNAM’s chemical faculty, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality that is environmentally and temperature-resistant.
If the signals sent by road covering were to be paid attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 yards for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Errer Naher, a researcher of the UNAM chemical faculty, and a researcher, if he adds that
In his lecture Technological View of Holes, read in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory, for which he is responsible, is developing a polymer-modified bitumen for the production of a mixture with the characteristics close to the bitumen, but with the best resistance and resistance as a bitumen.
Errera Nahera said this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of the oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are high molecular mass called asphalts, and others of low molecular mass called malts, which together give its character to the roadside.
The highly elastic behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it maintains a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures it retains a solid state.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but changes over the course of the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
The scientist noted that the streets of Mexico are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which consists of six layers of material, three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is the bitumen, composed of small stones dropped into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that constitutes this coating, he said, was immersed in the bitumen.
When moving vehicles and applying effort, it helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road covering.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, is placed the last layer, which is called the layer of wear, which is made of small stone, in fact sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the transport wheels, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road covering that will receive and disseminate the given effort, the wear layer also requires an appropriate thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature drops, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of the asphalt.
When the soil is raw, the water penetrates into the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of there, it causes the softening of all the coating layers and thus the formation of pits.
During the formation of the jaws, he said, first wears a layer of wear and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur immediately, this process should be paid attention to at the first signs according to the current repair programs.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating layer should always be associated with transport load and it is necessary to ensure compliance with this requirement in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of yams.
Rafael Errera said there is still much to study and do about bitumen, for example, bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help make holes with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
