With regard to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Kane and Rick Perry are competing in simplification and incompetence.
Can America, weakened by the crisis, lead a complex world with simple, more precisely, simplistic ideas?
If you listen to presidential candidates from Republicans, voters might believe it.
For several days, Mitt Romney, Herman Kane, Rick Perry and others have been multiplying loud, but deprived of the details of the foreign policy statement, which has traditionally been a stronghold of Republicans.
The slogans concerning China, Iran and aid to Israel are often confused with each other.
Mitt Romney, who has the best chance of being promoted from the “Old Good Party,” threatened to file a complaint against the Chinese to the WTO and accuse them of “manipulating their currency” is a sensitive topic for America, irritated by the migration of entire industries in its industry.
Even worse, if it leads to a trade war, he said.
John Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate in a complex foreign policy, has not been able to fight a position that strikes emotions.
He called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who holds the bottom of the rankings, remained unheard.
Reagan's style
