After Iraq, it does not believe in military interventions that are tied to the sand.
And, claiming that America needs to be rebuilt economically to revive its leadership, Obama is right.
North Stream, new gates for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Stream, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly at the bottom of the Baltic Sea, is launched.
It is intended to supply gas to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the performance of the orchestra and refined snacks, in the opening of the North Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany underwater.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague, Mart Rutte, have jointly returned a symbolic valve that controls the inflow of Russian gas into Western Europe.
According to the new pipeline, 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will arrive in Western Europe each year on the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready at the end of 2012, providing a total supply of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to all of France’s consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with the fierce resistance of Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream will actually allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia, threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop comparing the North Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", suggesting an alliance between Hitler and Stalin in order to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of the direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries that consume large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are already on the rise.
“This gas pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically binds us,” Fillon said, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Liebmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical step.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to circumvent the mining fields that had remained since World War II.
“The dog had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Mueller, a North Stream press secretary.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing equal to the weight of 242 Eiffel Towers, without breaks throughout its length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers abandoned it because Sweden was not thrilled that the Russian state company would live on its shores forever.
“In the event of an accident, we will interrupt the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Mueller.
So in case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to designers who designed seams, calculated to run only once every 100,000 years.
The state of the gas pipeline will be monitored by an underwater robot that pulls the ship, for external monitoring, as well as an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigarette-shaped apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by the flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second it gives accurate information about any metal deformation.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
The circulation of the gas is carried out only by its pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure and 100 bars on arrival.
Five companies have combined efforts to implement this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of its capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called North Stream, which was commissioned to build and operate a gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zürich, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of transport of gas.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, no matter how much gas will actually be transported,” says Jens Mueller.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be 7.4 thousand million euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be around 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay their expenses because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline comes from the Baltic Sea in Ljubmin on a sandy shore, planted by soft trees.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the exhaust gas terminal.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
Branded Moleskine Notebook
Moleskine, created by the Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste to the letter.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to identify by a rectangular black cover, by rubber, by yellow-white pages, as if desired over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, has decided to launch design notebooks for sale.
Maria Sebregondi, the company’s then consultant, took responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique, the moleskin - lacquered cotton fabric, used, for example, to cover the rockets.
It is claimed that this type of notebook is highly appreciated by writers and travellers.
“Moleskine has brought an old and forgotten thing in line with today’s taste that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become a managing brand in Modo Modo.
Success has arrived.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We went a long way from the first years of production, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Setting up a profile of a typical buyer is difficult, because the notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, have broad views and are educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small cities and has been able to gain widespread popularity.
“We followed the spirit of time and this new need in the letter despite the emergence of e-mail,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This distinctive cultural feature accompanies the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organised an exhibition "The Circular Path", where architects and artists showed their own notes.
In August, he also launched covers with a leopard drawing on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno.
Using its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, handles, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
Success that gave rise to jealousy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was purchased by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which added a new page to the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for people with disabilities begins today.
Despite the public charitable policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, namely 19 per cent versus 9 per cent for the general population.
Discouragement?
“No,” said Eric Blanche, the Director General of Adapt, an organization that organizes a Week of Disabled Employment.
"In 15 years we will have made significant progress."
“At that time, the unemployment rate was not two, but three times higher.”
“There is still a lot of work ahead.”
It should be said that there are still many barriers to employment for the disabled.
Among them are older: 37% over the age of 50 (17% on average).
They have a rather low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million higher education students only 10,000 disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to get back to work and that are the essence of the problem,” said Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slow.
The study, conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre Association on behalf of the Cité, found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “represented solid people in wheelchairs either mentally or mentally disabled.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of disabled workers, as set out in the law adopted in 1987.
The latest known figures, dating back to 2008, represent 2.6%.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blan, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for tax collection from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of "taxable" organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law that raised the tax created a lot of pressure on the company,” explains Pierre Blan.
“But this improvement also reflects the increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers versus 82% of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
